  "opinion": "As an electrician in Bologna, I’ve seen firsthand how stereotype threat plays out in technical fields. Stereotype threat isn’t just a theoretical concept—it’s the quiet anxiety that lingers when someone feels their identity might be judged as less capable in a specific context. For me, growing up in a family where my father had a bachelor’s degree and my mother an upper secondary education, I was always told to ‘be confident in your skills.’ But in STEM, especially when I’ve had to explain electrical systems to clients or troubleshoot complex circuits, the fear of being seen as ‘not smart enough’ can be paralyzing. I’ve noticed this most when I’m working with younger students who come from backgrounds where STEM isn’t traditionally seen as a path for them. They often freeze under pressure, not because they lack knowledge, but because they’re worried about confirming a stereotype. Should we address it? Absolutely. The solution isn’t about labeling people or creating new hierarchies—it’s about fostering environments where everyone feels safe to ask questions without fear of judgment. In my workshop, I’ve started by sharing my own struggles with confidence in technical subjects, which has helped break down barriers. It’s about creating a culture where mistakes are seen as learning opportunities, not failures. This approach aligns with my creative and agreeable nature—I believe in connecting through stories and empathy. In a world where STEM is often perceived as ‘for the few,’ it’s critical to make it accessible to all, starting with the understanding that everyone has the potential to contribute. My goal is to help others see themselves in the process, not as exceptions but as essential parts of the solution.",
